[2]
Date: Tue 24 Jan 2012
Source: Top Agrar online [German, transl. Sabine Zentis, edited]
http://www.topagrar.com/news/Rind-News-Schmallenberg-Virus-Die-grosse-Welle-kommt-vermutlich-erst-noch-691206.html


Schmallenberg-Virus: Probably, we haven't seen the worst yet
------------------------------------------------------------
The number of farms affected by SBV is increasing every day. But, according to Dr Martin Beer of the Friedrich-Loeffler-Institute, Riems Island, this is only the tip of the iceberg.

So far, cases in the Netherlands, Belgium and North Rhine-Westphalia, Lower Saxony and Hessen have been confirmed. But also Rhineland-Palatinate will probably not escape the virus that has never been found in Europe before, Dr. Beer concluded at a recent vet congress in Leipzig. Sheep farms are particularly affected. It is assumed that the infection has occurred in pregnant animals during the summer/fall of 2011. The birth of infected calves is therefore probably to be expected.

Dr. Martin Ganter of the Clinic of Small Ruminants, Hannover Veterinary School, thinks it is striking that the distribution area of SBV is similar to that of bluetongue disease. Possible explanation could be surface tectonics.

The virus is probably transmitted by biting midges and mosquitoes and infects the fetus in pregnant animals relatively quickly, causing a high rate of malformed, weak live animals and birth defects. The virus is primarily detected in the brains of infected animals. It gives rise to dramatic changes in the brain, to the extent that parts of the brain can be missing. Infection in adult animals leads to declining milk production and high fever.

Dr Ganter thinks that infection with SBV will be made notifiable soon; deliberations with the EU are ongoing.

